import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { url } from '../lib/url';
---

<Base title="How it works" description="A plain-language guide to how Fable Academy researches, writes, and ships a course — and how to steer it.">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Field manual</p>
    <h1>How a course gets made.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      No code required to read this. It explains what happens between a one-line request
      and a finished course on the shelf — and the one rule that keeps it improving.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="prose">

    <h2>Two halves: a factory and a shelf</h2>

    <p>
      This project is two things sharing one repository. The <strong>factory</strong> turns a single
      plain-English request — <em>"make a course on abstract algebra for someone who finished high-school
      maths"</em> — into a finished course. The <strong>shelf</strong> is this website, which automatically
      lists and serves every course the factory finishes. Drop a new course onto the shelf and it shows up
      here on its own; nobody edits the site to add it.
    </p>

    <h2>The one rule that matters</h2>

    <blockquote>
      <p><strong>Fix the factory, not the product.</strong></p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      When a course reads badly — too dull, too soothing, a confusing leap — the instinct is to patch that
      one page. Don't. The factory wrote that page by following written instructions, and it will write the
      next course the same way. So we change the <strong>instructions</strong>, then let the factory rebuild.
      A patched page fixes one course; a patched instruction fixes every course from now on. (The course you're
      reading about clock arithmetic had a confusing jump; the fix was a new rule about "bridging," not a one-off edit.)
    </p>

    <h2>The assembly line: six stations</h2>

    <p>
      A request walks down a line of six stations, in order. Each station does one job, writes down what it did,
      and hands its work to the next. Because every step is written to a file, you can open any of them and see
      exactly what the machine was thinking.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Research</strong> — gathers what the subject is, what the learner already needs to know, the
        trustworthy sources, and the usual places people get stuck.</li>
      <li><strong>Curriculum</strong> — decides the list of modules, their order, and what each one should teach.
        This is the most important checkpoint: it's where a human can read one page and approve the whole shape
        of the course before any writing happens — the cheapest place to fix a mistake.</li>
      <li><strong>Authoring</strong> — writes the modules. Several writers work at once, each on a different module
        and <em>blind to the others</em>. That's fast, but it's why two modules can drift apart or repeat themselves.</li>
      <li><strong>Editorial</strong> — one editor reads <em>all</em> the modules together and makes them feel like a
        single book: same names and symbols throughout, no module re-explaining what another already covered,
        confident tone, and smooth "bridges" wherever an everyday picture has to hand off to a precise definition.
        This station exists precisely to catch what the blind, parallel writers couldn't see.</li>
      <li><strong>Assembly</strong> — moves the finished modules out of the workshop and onto the shelf (the website),
        in the exact format the site expects.</li>
      <li><strong>Verify</strong> — the final check: are the maths and the structure valid, does the tone hold, and
        does the website actually build without errors? Only then does it ship.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Where everything lives</h2>

    <p>
      You don't need the file paths to understand the shape, but here it is in plain terms:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>The factory's rulebooks</strong> live in a folder of reference documents — the writing voice,
        the maths style, the teaching rules, the brand. These are the instructions we change when we "fix the factory."</li>
      <li><strong>Each station's job description</strong> sits in the station's own folder, written as a short contract:
        what it reads, what it does, what it produces, and how it checks itself.</li>
      <li><strong>The workshop</strong> is a dated folder for each course being built. Every station's working notes
        and drafts land here, so a finished course leaves a complete paper trail. Nothing here is thrown away when the next
        course is built — each run gets its own folder.</li>
      <li><strong>The shelf</strong> is the finished-courses area the website reads from. Workshop drafts never go here directly;
        only the assembly station crosses that line.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to find what went wrong</h2>

    <p>
      Because each station writes its work to a file, diagnosing a bad course is just reading backwards. If a course
      feels repetitive, the editorial station's notes show whether it caught the repetition. If a module teaches the
      wrong thing, the curriculum page shows whether the plan was wrong or the writing was. You read down the line until
      the defect first appears — that station's rulebook is what needs the fix.
    </p>

    <h2>Asking for a new course</h2>

    <p>
      You ask in one sentence: the subject, and who it's for. <em>"A course on the chemistry of cooking for curious
      adults with no science background."</em> The factory turns that into a written brief — including its own notes on
      what it's assuming about scope and difficulty — and walks the six stations. By default it runs straight through
      and only pauses at the curriculum checkpoint; you can ask it to stop and show you more, or just let it ship.
    </p>

    <h2>How a change reaches this site</h2>

    <p>
      When work is done, it's saved and pushed to the project's main copy. That push automatically rebuilds and
      republishes this website — no manual deploy step. So the path from "fix an instruction" to "the live site shows
      the better course" is: change the rulebook → rebuild the course → push → the site updates itself.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="muted-note">
      Want the technical version? The repository's <code>CLAUDE.md</code> and <code>CONTEXT.md</code> hold the full map
      and routing rules, and each station folder under <code>pipeline/</code> carries its own contract.
    </p>

    <p><a href={url('browse')}>← Back to the catalog</a></p>

  </div>
</Base>

